t">rary accommodation are considered, the current proposals will represent a significant increase in costs to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> both DWP and local authorities</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We believe that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">monthly housing assessments under </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Universal Credit </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> homeless households in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">non-exempt</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> temporary acc</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ommodation represents the single largest risk of increased costs to both DWP and local authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The application of the Benefit Cap to homeless households in B&amp;B will significantly increase the non-recoverable costs of temporary accommodation, payable by</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> local authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We have concerns over the practical application of Universal Credit for households in short-term temporary accommodation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">According to our calculations, based on local use of temporary accommodation, we believe that the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">cumulative effect </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">current proposals could result in an increased cost </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">to local authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of over 2000%</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We have set out our views and evidence in this report on the impact of each of the proposed changes</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">New Charter Housing Trust</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">New Charter Housing Trust is a Regi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">stered Provider of Social Housing, based in Tameside in Greater Manchester</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  The group also includes </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Gedling Homes, based in Gedling, Nottinghamshire</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and Knowsley Housing Options, based in Merseyside</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The New Charter Homes includes three contracted </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">services delivering homelessness advice and support. These are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Tameside Housing Advice – the statutory homelessness and housing advice service, contracted to Tameside MBC</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Gibson Terrace – short term, temporary supported accommodation for homeless families</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and vulnerable people </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Knowlsey Housing Options – the statutory homelessness and housing advice service, contracted to Knowsley MBC</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Through the delivery of these three services, New Charter has a detailed working knowledge of working with homeless </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">hou</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">seholds</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">. All three services work closely with </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the local authorities they are contract</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> to, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> ensure best practice performance, value for money and a reduction in overall costs.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Knowsley and Tameside have had considerable success in the past 2 years </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">in reducing the overall cost of temporary accommodation, both to DWP and the local authority.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Based on our analysis of the impact of the current proposals, we have serious concerns over the impact on homeless households, as well as the financial impact</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> on local authorities. We </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">urge the DWP to consider the regional implications of the current proposals to avoid significantly increased costs</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Monthly Anniversary Assessments</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The assessment of the housing element of universal credit on the anniversary of the claim (thereby in monthly cycles) represents one of our biggest areas of concern, and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of the greatest potential increase in</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> costs to DWP and local authorities if implemente</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">d as currently proposed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We are aware that Homeless Link has already developed a number of examples of how this will impact on individuals.  We can see no practical way of working within these proposals that will not lead to increased costs for DWP and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> to the Local Authority.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> Tameside and Knowsley our use B&amp;Bs is limited to statutory duty where no other suitable options are available, and for the minimum period of stay in order to reduce costs to DWP and the Authority.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Within Tameside, B&amp;B is</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> used as a last resort for those unable to move into short term supported accommodation.  Households are moved to lower cost accommodation at the first available opportunity.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In Knowsley the current temporary accommodation model is B &amp; B for the majority </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of placements.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Average weekly cost </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> B&amp;B in Tameside in 2013 is £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">967 per household</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and in Knowsley is £504 per household</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In order to ensure that the housing costs are taken into account, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> will have no option but to increase length of stay until after the anniversary of the claim.  For households making a new claim on the day of placement, this will be a full calendar month.  For those who have an existing claim, the period until the next a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">nniversary could be up to 8 weeks.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.6</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The need to ensure rental costs are met through the housing element, leading to a need to increase length of stay will mean that households will remain in high cost B&amp;B accommodation even after more suitable, lower co</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">st accommodation has become available, or where the council’s statutory duty has ended.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.7</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In 2012-13, t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">he a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">verage length of stay </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">per household </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Tameside </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> days, at an average cost of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">£165</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> per placement</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The increased length of stay in order to a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">llow for the housing assessment to take place </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would mean an increase of £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">1,934</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">£5,802</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> per household, per placement.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ven where customers have been placed in B&amp;B under a statutory duty within a day of the anniversary of their claim, there will be an</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> increased cost to DWP as universal credit is paid monthly in arrears.  Therefore, the customer or landlord will receive benefits relating to housing they may have only occupied for a matter of days.  The same will be true where customers move from higher </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">cost accommodation (such as B&amp;B) into social or private sector housing at a much lower cost.  The Housing Element relating to the high cost accommodation will continue to be paid until after the anniversary of the claim, again leading to greater cost to DW</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">P.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Benefit Cap</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The current proposals to apply the benefit cap to households living in temporary accommodation will negatively impact on households who have been placed in higher cost accommodation, such as hostels or B&amp;B.  As the duty to secure tem</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">porary accommodation under homelessness legislation is an absolute, there are occasions where placement in higher cost accommodation is unavoidable where no other suitable accommodation is available. The legislation and case law surrounding affordability i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">n regards to intentional homelessness means that the additional cost of this accommodation will necessarily fall to the local authority.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">For example, in Tameside the weekly cost of a single person in B&amp;B is £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">239</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and for a family is £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">434</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.  This leaves a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> shortfall of £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">149</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> or £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">313</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> respectively.  In Knowsley the costs </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of a single person in B &amp; B is £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">280</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and for a family is £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">504</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.  This leaves a shortfall of £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">190 or £383 respectively</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> The authority could require the household to make up this shortfall themselves, if they have the means to do so.  The likelihood is however, that a benefit dependant family would not have the means to meet this cost without a negative impact on essential </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">living costs.  This would be particularly true where households have been placed in B&amp;B and food costs will therefore be higher due to the inability to cook.  The household would therefore fall into arrears on their accommodation costs and be evicted from </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">their accommodation.  However, as the accommodation was unaffordable to them, the local authority would still retain a duty to secure temporary accommodation for them.  The only practical solution for an authority would be to meet the cost of the shortfall</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> for the duration of the placement.  This would increase the non-recoverable costs </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">to be paid by the authority.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In Knowsley this increase would be a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">14</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">% </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">weekly </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">rise on 2012-13 costs</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and 16% rise in Tameside</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.  If the current proposals for housing elem</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ent assessments are also </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">implemented, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">the combination of increased length of stay and increased non recoverable costs could lead to an annual increase in non-recoverable costs of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> over 2000%</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> in Tameside alone. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We are relieved to se</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">e that under the current proposals additional management costs relating to temporary accommodation will be met through Discretionary Housing Payments, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ensuring that universal credit will not be a bar to using temporary accommodation for universal credit cl</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">aimants.  However, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">we have serious concerns regarding the practical implications of placing customer in temporary ac</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">commodation on universal credit for both the claimant and the services supporting them.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Temporary accommodation is by its nature short t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">erm and households may make a number of moves within a short period before suitable long term accommodation is secured.  For example, where a customer is accepted as homeless in one authority but has no local connection and so the duty is transferred to an</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">other authority, the customer would be required to move to accommodation in the accepting authority area.  In Tameside and Knowsley customers placed in high cost accommodation may be required to move into lower cost accommodation when it becomes available,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> or may be moved into more accommodation more suitable to their needs (such as due to area or support needs) or for housing management issues.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Costs for each accommodation may vary greatly.  Customers under universal credit would be expected to notify </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">of a change of circumstances upon moving, as well as to manage their finances to ensure the correct rents are paid to the landlords of each accommodation, and that any underspend is retained to be repaid to DWP in the event of an over payment or to be used</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> to meet costs of higher rents where claims have not yet been processed.  We believe that this is too much to expect of households in crisis and will lead to claimants being subject to sanctions or facing further homelessness where housing costs are not me</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">t.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If managed payments to landlords were to be retained, this would reduce the hardship to the household, however </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would increase the workload and resource needs for local authorities.  In order to ensure that correct claims and notifications have been </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">made to universal credit, and to reconcile monthly payments in arrears to the rents paid to the landlords we anticipate that homelessness and housing advice services will need to employ additional staff.  In Tameside and Knowsley, which are small authoriti</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">es with a low number of temporary accommodation placements per quarter, we anticipate an additional member of staff for each service would be required to meet this need.  This would create an additional cost to the authorities of £</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">30,000</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">each.  Multiplied </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">by each authority area and factoring in larger authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">with large numbers of placements, this would create a significant additional cost for local authorities to meet in order to ensure households living in temporary accommodation are not faced with fu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">rther homelessness or benefit sanctions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Size Criteria </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Under the current proposals, customers living in temporary accommodation owned by the local authority are not exempt from the social sector size criteria, although those in most other types of</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> temporary accommodation are.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Knowsley Council are currently developing a dispersed model of temporary </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">accommodation. Properties will at time be under occupied in line with the size criteria and therefore result in a short fall for the occupier, who ar</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">e benefit dependent and would not have the means to meet the shortfall</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Managed payment of Rent to Landlords</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We are pleased that DWP is currently seeking views as to whether people receiving Universal Credit and living in temporary accommodation hav</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">e their rent paid straight to the landlords.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ur view</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">that it is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">essential that the current arrangements of direct payment to landlords </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> maintained.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Our reasons for this are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Households placed in temporary accommodation are usually vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">and/or chaotic and there is a high risk of late or non payment of rent, leading to rick of eviction</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Where households are vulnerable, local authorities may still be required to maintain a duty to households, even after they have been evicted from temporary </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">accommodation due to rent arrears. This creates both a funding and logistical problem for authorities, who may have difficulty finding alternative accommodation to meet the duty, and/or may be forced to pay landlords from their own fund to prevent further </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">risk of homelessness</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Many landlords currently providing temporary accommodation may refuse to accommodation where customers are responsible for payment of rent themselves due to the risk of non payment.  This will leave local authorities with a lack of tem</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">porary accommodation to meet their legal duties and may lead to increased costs due to statutory and judicial reviews.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further options to consider</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If the current proposals for monthly assessments of claims and change of circumstances are implemente</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, local authorities could consider a number of options:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If managed payments to landlords are retained, authorities could commission temporary accommodation for a minimum of 4 weeks.  The authority would pay the landlord directly and reclaim the housing element from universal credit in arrears.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If managed paym</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ents to landlords are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ended</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, authorities may still need to consider commissioning 4 weeks accommodation.  The authority would be responsible for payment to the landlord for the first 4 weeks or until the assessment has been completed.  The authority would </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">then seek to reclaim the housing element for this period from the customer.  Once affordability has been confirmed (by payment of the housing element through universal credit), the customer would be responsible for their own payment of rent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">A third option</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> would be for DWP to consider short term arrangements that would allow local authorities to reclaim the housing element through universal credit for a short period of time before the full benefit is paid directly to the customer.  A proposed timescale for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">this could be the 6 week statutory maximum for length of stay in B&amp;B.  This would further incentivise local authorities to reduce length of stay in B&amp;B.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The fundamental disadvantage to these options is that, in order to ensure the rental costs are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">cove</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">red;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> authorities will be required to place households until their first anniversary of their claim, leading to an increased length of stay and cost to local authorities and DWP</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">8.3</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Another option for local authorities would be to use 6 month ASTs in the p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">rivate rented sector in order to discharge temporary accommodation duty.  We understand that this is common practice in some of the southern local authorities.  This would resolve many of the issues around managed payments to landlords and the benefit cap.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">  We have 2 practical concerns regarding the operational logistics of implementing this where it is not already in practice:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Customers moving into the PRS will be required by landlords to provide a deposit and a month’s rent in advance.  Although a Bond co</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">uld be used, there will still be substantial financial implications for local authorities who would be likely to be responsible for meeting these costs.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Due to the payment of universal credit and the assessments on the monthly anniversary, customers movi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ng from high cost temporary accommodation into lower cost PRS accommodation would receive housing element at the higher cost for up to a month after moving, at greater cost to DWP.  This also risks vulnerable households facing sanctions that could impact o</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">n their ability to maintain their tenancy and risk further homelessness.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In areas such as Tameside and Knowsley, there has been significant success in recent years in increasing access to the PRS for vulnerable people and building </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">strong relationships with</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> suitable landlords.  To date the PRS accommodation that has been secured has been successful utilised to prevent homelessness through managed moved or through qualifying offers and discharge of duty to end homelessness.  Due to the limited number of prope</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">rties available in the boroughs at present, if the local authorities were required through these proposed reforms to use the PRS to discharge temporary accommodation duties</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, the whole of this stock portfolio would need to be transferred to meet temporary a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ccommodation duties.  This would reduce the number of options available to prevent homelessness through managed moves and return authorities to social housing as the only available option to discharge the full homelessness duty.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">If the temporary accommodat</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ion subsidy for licensed/leased accommodation is retained, using PRS to discharge duty for temporary accommodation will lead to an increased cost to DWP as households will be placed for a minimum of 6 months. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">8.4</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Authorities could consider commissioning a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">dditional exempt accommodation to use as temporary accommodation.  Given that budgets for 2013-14 have now been set, this would not be viable without grant funding from DCLG.  In addition, under the current proposals for social size criteria and benefit ca</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">ps, authorities may be concerned that such schemes would not be cost viable. In addition, the need to keep customers in accommodation for a minimum of 4 weeks in order to ensure housing element is met would mean that such schemes could not be used for cris</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">is bed spaces, leaving authorities needing to use B&amp;B to meet statutory temporary accommodation duties.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">9.0</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations for Action</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We believe that other options could be considered and that these, when combined with a national standard of good practice</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, could result in a substantial decrease in the National welfare spend on temporary accommodation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We propose that</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 83.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">DWP review the procedure for assessments of housing elements where households have been placed under homelessness legislation to allow for a</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> shorter period before assessment and therefore a shorter length of stay.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 83.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Households</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> living in temporary accommodation should not be placed on universal credit until phase 3 of the roll-out, in line with current proposals for households living in supported</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> accommodation.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 83.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> exemption currently proposed for the size criteria for non-local authority accommodation should also be extended to temporary accommodation owned by the local authority.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 83.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The current arrangements for direct payment of rent to landlords </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">be maintained for households in temporary accommodation</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We would welcome the opportunity to consult further with DWP and DCLG and to share the practices put in place in Tameside and Knowsley that have led to substantial reductions in costs locally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">would also urge DWP to carry out regional research and consultation to consider the impacts of the reforms on a National level and to gather the views of housing practitioners throughout the country.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">10 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>